#. Tag: title
#: storage_lvm.xml:524
#, no-c-format
msgid "Thinly provisioned logical volumes"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_lvm.xml:525
#, no-c-format
msgid "An LVM logical volume can optionally be thinly provisioned. Thin provisioning allows you to create logical volumes with sizes that overbook the available free space. You create a thin pool that contains unused space reserved for use with an arbitrary number of thin volumes. A thin volume is created as a sparse volume and space is allocated from a thin pool as needed. The thin pool can be expanded dynamically when needed for cost-effective allocation of storage space. Thinly provisioned volumes also support snapshots which can be managed with Snapper&mdash;see <xref linkend=\"cha-snapper\"/> for more information."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_lvm.xml:536
#, no-c-format
msgid "To set up a thinly provisioned logical volume, proceed as described in <xref linkend=\"pro-lvm-lv\"/> . When it comes to choosing the volume type, do not choose <guimenu>Normal Volume</guimenu> , but rather <guimenu>Thin Volume</guimenu> or <guimenu>Thin Pool</guimenu> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: storage_lvm.xml:544
#, no-c-format
msgid "<guimenu>Thin pool</guimenu>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_lvm.xml:547
#, no-c-format
msgid "The logical volume is a pool of space that is reserved for use with thin volumes. The thin volumes can allocate their needed space from it on demand."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: storage_lvm.xml:555
#, no-c-format
msgid "<guimenu>Thin volume</guimenu>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_lvm.xml:558
#, no-c-format
msgid "The volume is created as a sparse volume. The volume allocates needed space on demand from a thin pool."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: storage_lvm.xml:566
#, no-c-format
msgid "Thinly provisioned volumes in a cluster"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_lvm.xml:567
#, no-c-format
msgid "To use thinly provisioned volumes in a cluster, the thin pool and the thin volumes that use it must be managed in a single cluster resource. This allows the thin volumes and thin pool to always be mounted exclusively on the same node."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: storage_lvm.xml:577
#, no-c-format
msgid "Creating mirrored volumes"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_lvm.xml:578
#, no-c-format
msgid "A logical volume can be created with several mirrors. LVM ensures that data written to an underlying physical volume is mirrored onto a different physical volume. Thus even though a physical volume crashes, you can still access the data on the logical volume. LVM also keeps a log file to manage the synchronization process. The log contains information about which volume regions are currently undergoing synchronization with mirrors. By default the log is stored on disk and if possible on a different disk than are the mirrors. But you may specify a different location for the log, for example volatile memory."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_lvm.xml:589
#, no-c-format
msgid "Currently there are two types of mirror implementation available: \"normal\" (non-raid) <literal>mirror</literal> logical volumes and <literal>raid1</literal> logical volumes."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_lvm.xml:594
#, no-c-format
msgid "After you create mirrored logical volumes, you can perform standard operations with mirrored logical volumes like activating, extending, and removing."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: storage_lvm.xml:600
#, no-c-format
msgid "Setting up mirrored non-RAID logical volumes"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_lvm.xml:601
#, no-c-format
msgid "To create a mirrored volume use the <command>lvcreate</command> command. The following example creates a 500&nbsp;GB logical volume with two mirrors called <emphasis>lv1</emphasis> , which uses a volume group <emphasis>vg1</emphasis> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: storage_lvm.xml:607
#, no-c-format
msgid "&prompt.sudo;lvcreate -L 500G -m 2 -n lv1 vg1"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_lvm.xml:608
#, no-c-format
msgid "Such a logical volume is a linear volume (without striping) that provides three copies of the file system. The <literal>m</literal> option specifies the count of mirrors. The <literal>L</literal> option specifies the size of the logical volumes."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_lvm.xml:614
#, no-c-format
msgid "The logical volume is divided into regions of the 512 KB default size. If you need a different size of regions, use the <literal>-R</literal> option followed by the desired region size in megabytes. Or you can configure the preferred region size by editing the <literal>mirror_region_size</literal> option in the <filename>lvm.conf</filename> file."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: storage_lvm.xml:623
#, no-c-format
msgid "Setting up <literal>raid1</literal> logical volumes"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_lvm.xml:624
#, no-c-format
msgid "As LVM supports RAID you can implement mirroring by using RAID1. Such implementation provides the following advantages compared to the non-raid mirrors:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_lvm.xml:631
#, no-c-format
msgid "LVM maintains a fully redundant bitmap area for each mirror image, which increases its fault handling capabilities."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_lvm.xml:637
#, no-c-format
msgid "Mirror images can be temporarily split from the array and then merged back."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_lvm.xml:643
#, no-c-format
msgid "The array can handle transient failures."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_lvm.xml:648
#, no-c-format
msgid "The LVM RAID 1 implementation supports snapshots."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_lvm.xml:653
#, no-c-format
msgid "On the other hand, this type of mirroring implementation does not enable to create a logical volume in a clustered volume group."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_lvm.xml:657
#, no-c-format
msgid "To create a mirror volume by using RAID, issue the command"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: storage_lvm.xml:660
#, no-c-format
msgid "&prompt.sudo;lvcreate --type raid1 -m 1 -L 1G -n lv1 vg1"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_lvm.xml:661
#, no-c-format
msgid "where the options/parameters have the following meanings:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_lvm.xml:666
#, no-c-format
msgid "<literal>--type</literal> - you need to specify <literal>raid1</literal> , otherwise the command uses the implicit segment type <literal>mirror</literal> and creates a non-raid mirror."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_lvm.xml:673
#, no-c-format
msgid "<literal>-m</literal> - specifies the count of mirrors."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_lvm.xml:678
#, no-c-format
msgid "<literal>-L</literal> - specifies the size of the logical volume."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_lvm.xml:683
#, no-c-format
msgid "<literal>-n</literal> - by using this option you specify a name of the logical volume."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_lvm.xml:689
#, no-c-format
msgid "<literal>vg1</literal> - is a name of the volume group used by the logical volume."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_lvm.xml:695
#, no-c-format
msgid "LVM creates a logical volume of one extent size for each data volume in the array. If you have two mirrored volumes, LVM creates another two volumes that stores metadata."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_lvm.xml:700
#, no-c-format
msgid "After you create a RAID logical volume, you can use the volume in the same way as a common logical volume. You can activate it, extend it, etc."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: storage_lvm.xml:709
#, no-c-format
msgid "Automatically activating non-root LVM volume groups"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_lvm.xml:711
#, no-c-format
msgid "Activation behavior for non-root LVM volume groups is controlled in the <literal>/etc/lvm/lvm.conf</literal> file and by the <parameter>auto_activation_volume_list</parameter> parameter. By default, the parameter is empty and all volumes are activated. To activate only some volume groups, add the names in quotes and separate them with commas, for example:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: storage_lvm.xml:720
#, no-c-format
msgid "auto_activation_volume_list = [ \"vg1\", \"vg2/lvol1\", \"@tag1\", \"@*\" ]"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_lvm.xml:722
#, no-c-format
msgid "If you have defined a list in the <parameter>auto_activation_volume_list</parameter> parameter, the following will happen: <!-- # If auto_activation_volume_list is defined, each LV that is to be # activated with the autoactivation option (-\\-activate ay/-a ay) # is first checked against the list. If it does not match, the LV # is not activated. This list is checked as well as volume_list. # # \"vgname\" and \"vgname/lvname\" are matched exactly. # \"@tag\" matches any tag set in the LV or VG. # \"@*\" matches if any tag defined on the host is also set in the LV or VG # # auto_activation_volume_list = [ \"vg1\", \"vg2/lvol1\", \"@tag1\", \"@*\" ] -->"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_lvm.xml:740
#, no-c-format
msgid "Each logical volume is first checked against this list."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_lvm.xml:745
#, no-c-format
msgid "If it does not match, the logical volume will not be activated."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_lvm.xml:751
#, no-c-format
msgid "By default, non-root LVM volume groups are automatically activated on system restart by dracut. This parameter allows you to activate all volume groups on system restart, or to activate only specified non-root LVM volume groups."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: storage_lvm.xml:800
#, no-c-format
msgid "Resizing an existing volume group"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_lvm.xml:802
#, no-c-format
msgid "The space provided by a volume group can be expanded at any time in the running system without service interruption by adding physical volumes. This will allow you to add logical volumes to the group or to expand the size of existing volumes as described in <xref linkend=\"sec-lvm-lv-resize\"/> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_lvm.xml:810
#, no-c-format
msgid "It is also possible to reduce the size of the volume group by removing physical volumes. &yast; only allows to remove physical volumes that are currently unused. To find out which physical volumes are currently in use, run the following command. The partitions (physical volumes) listed in the <literal>PE Ranges</literal> column are the ones in use:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: storage_lvm.xml:818
#, no-c-format
msgid "&prompt.sudo;pvs -o vg_name,lv_name,pv_name,seg_pe_ranges\n"
      "root's password:\n"
